title: Mississippi Disenfranchisement code from MS AG

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Mississippi Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1) Any documents sufficient to identify the specific statutes of Mississippi Code which the Mississippi Office of the Attorney General has determined qualify as being included in the 22 disenfranchising general crimes, as described in the Attorney General's Opinion directed to The Honorable Wallace Heggie, dated July 7, 2009.

2) Any documents sufficient to explain, describe, or establish when the Office of the Attorney General determined each of the above statutes qualified as a disenfranchising crime.

The requested documents are for academic research and will eventually be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 7 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Robert Stewart, Ph.D.

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FOIA - FBI - William Lindsay White
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All records relating to or mentioning William Lindsay White (June 17, 1900 – July 26, 1973) - American journalist and foreign correspondent (see: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Lindsay_White )

Please conduct a thorough search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices - for both main-file records and cross-reference records for all relevant names, individuals, agencies and companies.  For reference, the associated file numbers for these records provided by the FBI are: 161-HQ-12494, 100-HQ-127094 Serial HQ1022, 100-HQ-481695 Serial HQ539, 100-HQ-459279, and 105-WF-20251 Serial 24.

If previously released records are available, then I request a rolling release consisting of those records while additional records are located and processed for release.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

J Ader

communications.subject: RE: [EXTERNAL EMAIL] -  RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1584961-000
communications.communication:
Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.  Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on “Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request” on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI’s FOIPA Program is searching the FBI’s indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 98 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 947 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 2,011 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 2,360 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

title: JPMorgan's Involvement in the Slave Trade

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: JPMorgan's Involvement in the Slave Trade
communications.communication:
MuckRock News
DEPT MR 146407
263 Huntington Ave
Boston, MA 02115

Date: 12/23/2023

U.S. Department of Justice
Civil Rights Division
FOIA/PA Unit
950 Pennsylvania Avenue, NW
Washington, D.C. 20530-0001

Subject: Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) Request – JPMorgan's Involvement in the Slave Trade

Dear FOIA Officer,

Under the provisions of the Freedom of Information Act, 5 U.S.C. § 552, I am submitting a request for access to and copies of all records held by the Civil Rights Division of the U.S. Department of Justice pertaining to JPMorgan's historical involvement in the slave trade.

For the purpose of this request, the records I seek include, but are not limited to:

1. Any correspondence, reports, or memoranda exchanged between the Civil Rights Division and JPMorgan during the historical period when the institution may have been involved in the slave trade.

2. Documents related to any investigations, audits, or legal actions taken by the Civil Rights Division against JPMorgan regarding its historical practices in connection with the slave trade.

3. Any internal policies, guidelines, or communications within the Civil Rights Division that pertain to investigating and addressing historical injustices, including those related to financial institutions and their involvement in morally reprehensible practices such as the slave trade.

4. Records indicating any efforts or initiatives undertaken by the Civil Rights Division to proactively address or disclose information related to the historical involvement of financial institutions, including JPMorgan, in the slave trade.

In support of this request, I would like to draw your attention to relevant case law, including but not limited to:

- **National Archives and Records Administration v. Favish, 541 U.S. 157 (2004):** Emphasizing the importance of balancing privacy interests against the public interest in disclosure when considering FOIA requests.

- **Department of Justice v. Reporters Committee for Freedom of the Press, 489 U.S. 749 (1989):** Underscoring the need for a functional analysis of the requested documents, focusing on the nature and content of the information rather than the identity of the parties involved.

Should any portion of the requested records be deemed exempt from disclosure, I request the release of any reasonably segregable non-exempt portions in accordance with 5 U.S.C. § 552(b). If an entire document is exempt, I request a detailed justification, citing specific FOIA exemptions, and provision of an exemption log as per Vaughn v. Rosen, 484 F.2d 820 (D.C. Cir. 1973).

Please be aware of your obligation under the law not to destroy any records potentially responsive to this request. Any withholding, redaction, or destruction of responsive records without proper justification constitutes a violation of the FOIA and is subject to litigation, as confirmed in Kissinger v. Reporters Committee for Freedom of the Press, 445 U.S. 136, 150 (1980).

Enclosed is a letter requesting a fee waiver for the processing of this request. As an independent investigative journalist associated with TransparencyReport.pw, I believe that the information I seek is in the public interest, and its disclosure contributes significantly to public understanding of the operations or activities of the government.

If the enclosed waiver is not accepted and there are any potential charges in excess of $200 associated with fulfilling my request, please inform me in advance.

As stipulated by the FOIA, I look forward to your response within twenty business days (5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(A)(i)).

Thank you for your prompt attention to this matter.

Sincerely,
Jordan Lassiter
Independent Investigative Journalist
TransparencyReport.pw
Email: Jordan@Lassiter.eu

Enclosure: Fee Waiver Request Letter

Please be aware: All communications related to this request, including incoming and outgoing communications, will be publicly available on MuckRock.com. Additionally, any correspondence in relation to this request will be instantly published on the platform.

Renee

title: Bonding of Personnel and Related Policies - Capital Region BOCES July 2023 Meeting

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: Bonding of Personnel and Related Policies - Capital Region BOCES July 2023 Meeting
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

Records related to the bonding of personnel as discussed in item 34 of the Re-Organization Meeting held in July 2023.

Specifically, I am interested in:

Copies of any contracts or agreements pertaining to the additional Crime Indemnity coverage purchased for the Treasurer, Deputy Treasurer, and Director of Business Operations, including the coverage amounts of $5,000,000 for the Treasurer and Deputy Treasurer, and $4,900,000 for the Director of Business Operations.
The policies and any amendments related to these contracts, including the policy numbers and detailed descriptions of the coverage.
Any internal memos, correspondence, or documents that discuss the decision-making process or rationale behind the bonding amounts and the selection of personnel for this coverage.
Minutes or transcripts of any meetings where the bonding of these personnel and related policies were discussed, if not fully covered in the July 2023 Re-Organization Meeting minutes.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jackson Parker

title: Select Aldermanic Fair Workweek Emails (Chicago Assets, Information and Services)

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: Select Aldermanic Fair Workweek Emails (Chicago Assets, Information and Services)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

All emails and attachments sent or received during the period 1/1/2018–12/31/2019 by Aldermen John Arena, Patrick O'Connor, Carlos Ramirez-Rosa, Susan Sadlowski-Garza, or Tom Tunney that contain the (non-case-sensitive) phrases "fair workweek", "fair work week", or "fair scheduling." I have attached a list of 29 email addresses pertinent to this request, including aliases and Ward addresses. Please search for responsive records associated with any of these 29 addresses.

I am requesting these records for non-commercial research purposes. The records will be made available to the general public.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer that the request be filled electronically, if possible, by e-mail attachment.

Note that, in order to obtain all responsive records regardless of which public body holds them, I am submitting this request concurrently to the Chicago City Council; City Clerk; Mayor's Office; and Department of Assets, Information, and Services.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Peter Fugiel
Postdoctoral Research Fellow
Rutgers School of Management and Labor Relations

communications.subject: RE: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request #F059394-102323
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Miranda,

Thank you for your letter dated October 30. I recognize the need to weigh the burden of fulfilling the request against the public interest in the information. I am surprised that your search returned 3,710 pages of responsive records. That figure is 7 times greater than the number of pages returned by a similar search conducted by the Mayor's Office (509 pages) and 9 times greater than the responsive records returned by the City Council Committee on Workforce Development (392 pages). 

Before I narrow my request, could you please confirm that your office conducted a search for the exact, compound phrases "fair workweek", "fair work week", or "fair scheduling"? If the initial search did not use quotation marks or Boolean operators to filter out partial matches containing only one key word (e.g. "scheduling"), it likely returned many irrelevant results. For example, a Google search of the key words (fair workweek fair scheduling) without quotation marks yields more than 5.5 million results (https://www.google.com/search?q=fair+scheduling+fair+workweek). By contrast, enclosing the relevant phrases in quotation marks ("fair workweek" "fair scheduling") yields only 1,390 results (https://www.google.com/search?q=%22fair+scheduling%22+%22fair+workweek%22). 

I appreciate your offer to share an index of the emails. Assuming the index includes the date of each email, it would shed light on the relevance of the initial search results. Most of the public discussion and legislative action around the Chicago Fair Workweek Ordinance occurred between June 2018 and July 2019 with a peak around June or July 2019. The date distribution of search results should reflect this, with relatively few results from earlier in 2018 or later in 2019. If that is not the case in your initial search, it likely contains irrelevant results that can be filtered out through more precise specification of the search parameters.

If the initial search was conducted using the exact parameters requested, then I would be willing to narrow my request. I am most interested in emails and attachments sent or received by Aldermen John Arena, Carlos Ramirez-Rosa, and Tom Tunney, since they were not included in the records previously provided to me. According to my list (Aldermanic_addresses_to_search.xlsx), there are 18 email addresses or aliases associated with these 3 Aldermen. To be clear, I am requesting all emails and attachments sent or received during the period 1/1/2018–12/31/2019 by Aldermen John Arena, Carlos Ramirez-Rosa, or Tom Tunney that contain one or more of the non-case-sensitive, compound phrases "fair workweek", "fair work week", or "fair scheduling." 

As you review my request, I ask that you take into account the considerable public interest in this information. The Chicago Fair Workweek Ordinance establishes the most expansive set of working time regulations since the Fair Labor Standards Act of 1938. While similar scheduling legislation has passed in a dozen other cities, Chicago is the only jurisdiction in the country to cover manufacturing, warehouse, and health care as well as retail and hospitality workers with comparable protections. My assessment of the public interest in this matter is informed by my expertise as an academic researcher who specializes in labor standards and scheduling practices. I have requested these records as part of the first systematic study of scheduling legislation, a project in which the National Science Foundation found sufficient intellectual merit and public interest to award me a competitive Postdoctoral Research Fellowship (#2203815).

I look forward to your clarification of the initial search results and continued assistance with my request.

Sincerely,

Peter Fugiel, PhD

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Records pertaining to the capture, diagnosis and euthanization of P-22
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting a copy of all reports, memos and correspondence related to the capture, diagnosis and subsequent euthanization of the mountain lion known as P-22.

Your department's leading role in the administration of this string of event was documented in this Dec. 17, 2022 story published by the Los Angeles Times

https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2022-12-17/p22-obituary-celebrity-mountain-lion-cougar-puma-griffith-park-california

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ben Welsh

RE: PUBLIC RECORDS ACT REQUEST of December 17, 2022, Reference # R005993-121922 
Dear Ben Welsh, 

This letter is in response to the above-referenced request you submitted to the Department of Fish and Wildlife (Department) pursuant to the Public Records Act (PRA) (Govt. Code, § 6250 et seq.) on December 17, 2022. 

The Department is initiating a search for records responsive to your request and will make available for inspection or provide copies of all responsive records, if any, that it is able to locate through reasonable efforts and that are not privileged or exempt from disclosure pursuant to the PRA or other applicable law. The Department will seek to make such records available as soon as reasonably possible. In the event the Department will be unable to make the records available within 90 days of your initial request, we will contact you to discuss the matter. 

The PRA requires disclosure of existing records in the possession, custody, or control of a public agency. If the Department locates existing records responsive to your request, Department staff will assemble the disclosable records. You may elect to receive copies of the records or to inspect them in person: 
 
  * If you chose to receive copies electronically, documents maintained in electronic format will be transmitted electronically whenever possible through the PRA Records Center. 
  * If the Department needs to deliver hard copies, you will be charged a copying fee of $.15 per page. The Department will notify you of the total cost prior to mailing the records. Please note the Department cannot waive or reduce these fees and costs for any reason.  Once staff are able to return to their offices to make and send the copies, they will be sent to you. 
  * If you chose to inspect the records in person, you will be notified of the availability of the records for inspection. 
If you have any questions or need additional information, please contact us and reference PRA No. R005993-121922.  You may also call (916) 654-3821. 

Sincerely, 

Lacy Bauer 

To monitor the progress or update this request please log into the Public Records Center (https://u8387778.ct.sendgrid.net/ls/click?upn=6HtRfOYLt5fXvpttM-2FU1HZPEhFU-2Bvy2oqrlHBe5M0RGAeT-2B4qUykOWV59A9EEIaMPR3Z61l1qOuhakTThE-2F77Z5F1t1TcgerLoFymh-2FS3eHKUPDgpIT9msrJlkj2-2FcFMQf4B_jdd-2FkHGaRoBK3G4V2uO0vDbhYgkiU4-2B1YD8HTfIqczN55dF3mSU410DOqyTYAD4gF6i8BnQQGcZmYaua-2FJTGomeZaZT92VrODt31-2BkV3BTtdiA2rLWvqMWgNlJHxVDOedpO6nP1e4uaWAoQetVi-2Fu20KssisrWKwK1GWLTmJx1iuDhr4-2BK4fg85r-2FeIFyzr908koPXgTHbSTRx9WLHlIlkM8rVj-2B5dnhAodBgIJPcjg-3D)

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Records pertaining to P-22
communications.communication:
Dear Ben Welsh,

I am writing to you regarding the PRA request below. CDFW has not received responses to emails sent to you via our PRA platform, GovQA, dated 12/19/22, 12/21/22, and 8/1/23. If you did not receive those communications and need assistance accessing the records that were released, please contact CDFW for technical assistance with the GovQA platform.

CDFW is planning to close the PRA request on Friday, March 22, 2024, unless communication is received asking to keep the request open. Please note that even if CDFW does close the request, you can always submit a new request.

From Ben Welsh, MuckRock News:
To Whom It May Concern: Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records: I am requesting a copy of all reports, memos and correspondence related to the capture, diagnosis and subsequent euthanization of the mountain lion known as P-22. Your department's leading role in the administration of this string of event was documented in this Dec. 17, 2022 story published by the Los Angeles Times https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2022-12-17/p22-obituarycelebrity-mountain-lion-cougar-puma-griffith-park-california<https://gcc02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.latimes.com%2Fcalifornia%2Fstory%2F2022-12-17%2Fp22-obituarycelebrity-mountain-lion-cougar-puma-griffith-park-california&data=05%7C01%7CJordan.Traverso%40wildlife.ca.gov%7Cf5642ee8bb2e4219a59908dae2befc37%7C4b633c25efbf40069f1507442ba7aa0b%7C0%7C0%7C638071607316299630%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=DU7rmfW7LVSbnpuNvV5R9%2BCJ4T0KjRJBhK8uDLnmvYA%3D&reserved=0<https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2022-12-17/p22-obituarycelebrity-mountain-lion-cougar-puma-griffith-park-california%3chttps:/gcc02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.latimes.com%2Fcalifornia%2Fstory%2F2022-12-17%2Fp22-obituarycelebrity-mountain-lion-cougar-puma-griffith-park-california&data=05%7C01%7CJordan.Traverso%40wildlife.ca.gov%7Cf5642ee8bb2e4219a59908dae2befc37%7C4b633c25efbf40069f1507442ba7aa0b%7C0%7C0%7C638071607316299630%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=DU7rmfW7LVSbnpuNvV5R9%2BCJ4T0KjRJBhK8uDLnmvYA%3D&reserved=0>> The requested documents
will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not. Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires. Sincerely, Ben Welsh

Thank you,
Lacy Bauer

Lacy Bauer (she/her/hers)
Senior Staff Attorney
Office of the General Counsel
California Department of Fish and Wildlife
(916) 201-2556 [mobile]
lacy.bauer@wildlife.ca.gov

title: New construction permits in the last 2 years

communications.subject: Nevada Public Records Act Request: New construction permits in the last 2 years
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Nevada Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records sufficient to show all new construction permits issued by the Nevada EPA for Washoe, Storey, and Lyon counties in the period from 2022 - present, including but not limited to facility ID, applicant, address, date of application, date of issue/approval, and type of facility. Please provide this in a tabular format such as a CSV or Excel file.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ariel Smith

communications.subject: RE: Nevada Public Records Act Request: New construction permits in the last 2 years
communications.communication:
Good morning, Ariel,

Are you just looking for Air permits? I’m in the Bureau of Air Quality and want to verify that’s all you need. Nevada Division of Environmental Protection Air Bureau doesn’t have authority in Washoe country, they have their own air program.  You would need to contact them directly for any air permits. I will assemble a list of air permits we’ve issued for Lyon and Storey county and get that to you by the end of the week.

Regards,

Misti Gower
Management Analyst III
Administrative Branch Supervisor, Bureau of Air Quality Planning
Nevada Division of Environmental Protection
mgower@ndep.nv.gov<mailto:mgower@ndep.nv.gov>
(O) 775-687-9494

title: Residence Halls Violations (University of Central Florida)

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Residence Halls Violations (University of Central Florida)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

Records of all liquor displinary violations, drug disciplinary violations, reports of rape, reports of fondling, and reports of statutory rape from student residence halls dating from January 1, 2014 to December 31, 2019 (inclusive). I am requesting this information have the following information (but not limited to): exact date reported of the violation (e.g., the month, day, and year) and type of violation (e.g., liquor, drug, rape, fondling, statutory rape violation).

If this data can be given in a spreadsheet format (e.g., .xls, .csv, .xlsx) this would be most appreciated.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Michael Topper

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter.

I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

{ Whittney Evans }

communications.subject: RE: [EXTERNAL EMAIL] -  RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1469387-000
communications.communication:
Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.  Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on "Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request" on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI's FOIPA Program is searching the FBI's indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 104 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 853 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 1,786 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 2,500 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

title: Data Request for Local Ballot Initiatives/Referenda

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Data Request for Local Ballot Initiatives/Referenda
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting data on local ballot initiatives/referenda that took place in the state since 1972. Specifically, I need the following information to be included in the data.

1. Text of the ballot initiative/referendum
2. Local government where the election took place.
3. County where the local government is located
4. Election date
5. Result of election (votes for, votes against, pass/fail)
6. Threshold to pass (50%, two-thirds, etc)

I have located this data at the following link: https://data.ca.gov/dataset/election-data/resource/67e83a65-2b55-41ec-9420-b33b666d4711

However, the data at this link does not contain the full text of the initiative/referendum. In addition, it contains only information on elections dating back to 1986, while I request data for elections dating back to 1972.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

communications.communication:
Dear Jimin,

Thank you for contacting the California Secretary of State with your request for records pursuant to the California Public Records Act. A copy of your request is attached.

The Secretary of State has a portion of the requested information on local ballot initiatives and referenda from the years 1995 to 2022.  That information  can be accessed on the Secretary of State’s website through the following links: https://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/ballot-measures/resources-and-historical-information/reports-county-and-municipal-initiative-measures; https://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/county-city-school-district-ballot-measure-election-results.

For historical statewide initiative resources, you may find useful information on the Secretary of State’s website through the following link: https://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/ballot-measures/resources-and-historical-information/history-california-initiatives

In addition, you may wish to contact local county elections offices for any other information pertaining to local ballot initiatives and referenda.

All files on or related to Grace Paley, a prominent writer, academic, and activist, whose death in 2007 was widely reported by the media: https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/23/books/23cnd-paley.html

title: shapefile for election precincts in March 2024 election

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: shapefile for election precincts in March 2024 election
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

a GIS shapefile of the electoral precincts as they defined for the March, 2024 election

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Forest Gregg

Good afternoon, Mr Gregg,
For your (and others') convenience, the Board has already uploaded our current precincts' shapefile to the "Chicago Data Portal" (https://data.cityofchicago.org/ ). Since they carry a number of  such files, one fairly easy way to find the file - using their search bar - is to 
1. search for "precincts", then 
2. scroll through the resulting list to "Boundaries - Ward Precincts (2023- )"
You'll probably find two entries, a "Map" view which will show you precincts, and another "DataSet" version with a slightly more direct button to the download - although you can reach the same dataset via the map view as well.  
This precinct map, with 1291 precincts, covers not only this election but the two Municipal Elections (Feb General and April Runoff) in 2023.  In fact, it's nearly the same for the Nov 2022 General (which had 1290 precincts - the first election which we administered using the "2022 Wards", derived and approved from the 2020 Census ReDistricting).  Between Nov 2022 and Feb 2023, one precinct - Ward 24 pct 16 - was split in two, subsequently becoming precincts 16 and 20.  Merge Wd 24, pcts 16 & 20 in this file, and it should describe the Nov 2022 results as well .  Previous elections (including the 2022 spring Primary ) used the Wards (and precincts) from the prior Census' redistricting.

We also have a number of Ward & Precinct maps, Legislative District maps, Lists of precincts within Legislative Districts, along with election results, etc, via our website "chicagoelections.gov",   Currently the March 19 primary results are still being counted, due to obligatory waiting periods for mail ballots, provisional ballots, etc. 

I hope this answers your question.

title: Data Request for Local Ballot Initiatives/Referenda (Colorado Secretary Of State - Elections Division)

communications.subject: Colorado Open Records Act Request: Data Request for Local Ballot Initiatives/Referenda (Colorado Secretary Of State - Elections Division)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Colorado Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting data on local ballot initiatives/referenda that took place in the state since 1972. Specifically, I need the following information to be included in the data.

1. Text of the ballot initiative/referendum
2. Local government where the election took place.
3. County where the local government is located
4. Election date
5. Result of election (votes for, votes against, pass/fail)
6. Threshold to pass (50%, two-thirds, etc)

This website from California provides a good example of the type of data I am requesting:
https://data.ca.gov/dataset/election-data/resource/67e83a65-2b55-41ec-9420-b33b666d4711

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jimin Han

title: Leak referrals and consultations (Securities and Exchange Commission)

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Leak referrals and consultations (Securities and Exchange Commission)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Copies of documents, including but not limited to emails, memos, letters, reports, briefs and call logs, referring to, discussing or generated as a result of referrals to and consultations with the Federal Bureau of Investigation and other components of the Department of Justice (Criminal Division, Civil Division, National Security Division, the Attorney General's office, etc.), regarding instances of unauthorized disclosures of information (AKA leaks) for investigation and/or prosecution between January 20, 1981 (or the date of creation of this agency, whichever came first) and the present. 

I request "news media" status and a fee waiver, see attached.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Emma Best

PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST RCW 42.56:

I request any/all public records of the following:

1.	COCAINE – Use of cocaine by Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers on or off elementary school grounds.
2.	FIREARMS/HANDGUNS – Names of all Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers in possession of HANDGUNS or FIREARMS on elementary school grounds.
3.	KIDNAPPING – any records or police reports referencing KIDNAPPING and current or former Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers.
4.	RESISTING ARREST - any records or police reports referencing RESISTING ARREST by current or former Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers.
5.	CARJACKING - any records or police reports referencing CARJACKING and current or former Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers.
6.	DRIVING UNDER THE INFLUENCE OF DRUGS OR ALCOHOL - any records or police reports referencing DRIVING UNDER THE INFLUENCE OF DRUGS OR ALCOHOL by current or former Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers.
7.	HIT AND RUN - any records or police reports referencing HIT AND RUN by current or former Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers.
8.	OBSTRUCTION - any records or police reports referencing OBSTRUCTION by current or former Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers.
9.	CRIMINAL or CIVIL CHARGES - copies of all CRIMINAL or CIVIL CHARGES of any current or former Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers.
10.	GUILTY PLEAS – copies of all STATEMENT OF DEFENDANT ON PLEA OF GUILTY entered into by any former Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers.
11.	COMPLAINTS - any records referencing COMPLAINTS by the POLICE or the GENERAL PUBLIC about current or former Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers.

communications.subject: Police Records Request :: D000157-020424
communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 

02/09/2024 
Re:  Public Records Request No. D000157-020424 
Dear Sunrise Parent: 
The purpose of this letter is to acknowledge receipt of your request for public records received on 2/4/2024 and to request clarification on the records you are requesting. 

You requested the following: 

PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST RCW 42.56: 

I request any/all public records of the following: 

1. COCAINE – Use of cocaine by Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers on or off elementary school grounds. 
2. FIREARMS/HANDGUNS – Names of all Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers in possession of HANDGUNS or FIREARMS on elementary school grounds. 
3. KIDNAPPING – any records or police reports referencing KIDNAPPING and current or former Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers. 
4. RESISTING ARREST - any records or police reports referencing RESISTING ARREST by current or former Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers. 
5. CARJACKING - any records or police reports referencing CARJACKING and current or former Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers. 
6. DRIVING UNDER THE INFLUENCE OF DRUGS OR ALCOHOL - any records or police reports referencing DRIVING UNDER THE INFLUENCE OF DRUGS OR ALCOHOL by current or former Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers. 
7. HIT AND RUN - any records or police reports referencing HIT AND RUN by current or former Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers. 
8. OBSTRUCTION - any records or police reports referencing OBSTRUCTION by current or former Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers. 
9. CRIMINAL or CIVIL CHARGES - copies of all CRIMINAL or CIVIL CHARGES of any current or former Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers. 
10. GUILTY PLEAS – copies of all STATEMENT OF DEFENDANT ON PLEA OF GUILTY entered into by any former Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers. 
11. COMPLAINTS - any records referencing COMPLAINTS by the POLICE or the GENERAL PUBLIC about current or former Northshore School District Elementary School Principals or teachers. 

Please clarify the following: 

1. COCAINE – Please provide a name(s) of a Northshore School District (NSD) Elementary School teacher or former teacher you believe has been in possession of cocaine. 
2. FIREARMS/HANDGUNS – Concealed weapon dissemination is statutorily prohibited and would violate the subject’s right to privacy. This information would be exempt from disclosure. See RCW 42.56.240(4) and RCW 9.41.129. 
3. KIDNAPPING – Please provide a name(s) of a current or former NSD Elementary School Principal or teacher who you believe was involved in a Kidnapping report. 
4. RESISTING ARREST – Please provide a name(s) of a current or former NSD Elementary School Principal or teacher who you believe was involved in a resisting arrest report. 
5. CARJACKING – Please provide a name(s) of a current or former NSD Elementary School Principal or teacher who you believe was involved in a carjacking report. 
6. DRIVING UNDER THE INFLUENCE OF DRUGS OR ALCOHOL - Please provide a name(s) of a current or former NSD Elementary School Principal or teacher who you believe was involved in a DUI report. 
7. HIT AND RUN - Please provide a name(s) of a current or former NSD Elementary School Principal or teacher who you believe was involved in a Hit and Run report. Also please note, in a hit and run incident we will often only have the victim’s information. 
8. OBSTRUCTION - Please provide a name(s) of a current or former NSD Elementary School Principal or teacher who you believe was involved in an Obstruction report. 
9. CRIMINAL or CIVIL CHARGES - Please provide a name(s) of a current or former NSD Elementary School Principal or teacher who you believe was involved in criminal or civil charges. 
10. GUILTY PLEAS – Guilty pleas are entered by the Court. You will need to contact the various local courts for guilty pleas. 
11. COMPLAINTS - Please provide a name(s) of a current or former NSD Elementary School Principal or teacher who you believe was referenced in a complaint. I believe NSD would hold the records in regards to complaints on current or former NSD principals or teachers. Typically we only see complaints in regards to situations and/or specific officers  Please clarify what complaints you would like to receive. 

I can search the principal names provided in your request, but other than those names I have no way of knowing any other names of NSD current or former principals or teachers. In addition, it should be noted the two Principals involved recently in the news were NSD principals, but were not principals within the City of Bothell Police Department’s jurisdiction. The following elementary schools are within the City of Bothell’s jurisdiction: Canyon Creek Elementary, Crystal Springs Elementary, Frank Love Elementary, Maywood Hills Elementary, Shelton View Elementary, Westhill Elementary, Woodin Elementary and Woodmoor Elementary. See attached map of City of Bothell’s jurisdiction. 

Lastly, please provide a searchable date range. 

If we do not hear from you with clarification by 2/26/2024, we will interpret your request as only searching the elementary schools within our jurisdiction for the names provided in your request. 

It is anticipated records responsive to the foregoing interpretation will be ready by 3/4/2024. 

Please feel free to contact me at 425-487-5126 or respond to this email with any questions. 
Sincerely, 
Jessica Ertel 
Public Records Specialist, Police

Please feel free to contact me at 425-487-5126 or respond to this email with any questions. 
Sincerely, 
Jessica Ertel

title: FOIL Request for Information on COVID-19 Tests and Masks Distribution to Schools (Sole Supervisory District Of Albany-schoharie-schenectady-saratoga Counties And Boces (capital Region))

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: FOIL Request for Information on COVID-19 Tests and Masks Distribution to Schools (Sole Supervisory District Of Albany-schoharie-schenectady-saratoga Counties And Boces (capital Region))
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

1. All communications between the Governor's Office and/or the State Education Department and/or Boards of Cooperative Educational Services (BOCES) regarding the distribution of COVID-19 rapid test kits and N-95 and KN-95 masks to schools, dated from January 1, 2023, to the present.
  
2. Records of all requests submitted by school districts and BOCES for COVID-19 rapid test kits and N-95 and KN-95 masks, dated from January 1, 2023, to the present.

3. Inventory records detailing the quantities of COVID-19 rapid test kits and N-95 and KN-95 masks that have been delivered to each BOCES for distribution to school districts, dated from January 1, 2023, to the present.

4. Any and all guidelines, memos, or advisories issued by the Governor's Office or the New York State Department of Health (DOH) regarding the distribution of COVID-19 rapid test kits and masks to schools, dated from January 1, 2023, to the present.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jackson Parker

communications.communication:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

All written communications from or to Katie Strickland from the following individuals:
Jason Weida, 
Stefan Grow
Pedro Allende, or
John Schrader

All documents relevant to the hiring of Sketch Piers in his current capacity, including the qualifications of any other candidates considered, as well as any record of Piers' previous job performance, and previous salary rates, during his tenure with the State of Florida.

All allegations of misconduct, determinations of misconduct, investigations, communications or inquiries, either resolved or pending (to the extent they are public record pursuant to FL. Stat. Ch. 119) which reference Katie Strickland and have been directed to the above listed individuals in either an official capacity or to the respective agencies under their purview.

The travel requests, approvals, calendars, and all documents pertaining to official state travel including food and lodging expenses of both Katie Strickland and Sketch Piers from the dates 1/1/2021 to the present, including prospective travel that has not occurred but has generated responsive documents as of the date of this request.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Eagle Springs liquor orders
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

Purchase orders for liquor, wine and beer for Eagle Springs Golf Course Restaurant from 2022-present day

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Chase Galloway

communications.subject: Nevada Public Records Act Request: Police Logs at University of Nevada Football Games
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Nevada Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any police logs related to incidents at football games for the Nevada Wolfpack during the 2023 season. 
Calls to service or arrests made at football games in the 2023 season.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Andrew Maples

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Donald Barr
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records relating to, mentioning, or generated as a result of investigation into Donald Barr (August 8, 1921 – February 5, 2004). Proof of death is not required as his death was widely reported: https://www.nytimes.com/2004/02/10/nyregion/donald-barr-82-headmaster-and-science-honors-educator.html. Records are likely to exist on Barr as he was nominated in 1983 to be part of the National Council on Educational Research, a now-defunct body of the Department of Education.

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records for all relevant names, individuals, agencies and companies. This is also to include any responsive records held in offsite locations, such as the Alexandria Records Center. Please include both investigatory and non-investigatory records in your search. If any potentially responsive records have been destroyed and/or transferred to NARA, then I request copies of the destruction or transfer slips as well as any other documentation relating to, mentioning or describing said transfer or destruction, to include but not be limited to confirmation that the Bureau has no other copies of said records. If previously released records are available, then I request a rolling release consisting of those records while additional records are located and processed for release.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Paul Galante

communications.communication:
Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.  Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on “Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request” on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI’s FOIPA Program is searching the FBI’s indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 98 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 947 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 2,011 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 2,360 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: C. Boyden Gray
communications.communication:
Dear FBI:

This is a request for records under the Freedom of Information Act.

RECORDS REQUESTED

All records related to Clayland Boyden Gray. Mr. Gray was a lawyer and diplomat who served as White House Counsel from 1989 to 1993 and as U.S. Ambassador to the European Union from 2006 to 2007. He was born on 6 February 1943 in Winston-Salem, NC, USA. He died on 21 May 2023.

PROOF OF DEATH
Obituaries for Mr. Gray appeared in numerous national media, including the New York Times, https://www.nytimes.com/2023/05/21/obituaries/c-boyden-gray-dead.html and the Washington Post, https://www.washingtonpost.com/obituaries/2023/05/21/c-boyden-gray-white-house-counsel-president-ghw-bush-dies-80/.

CROSS-REFERENCE SEARCH

Please conduct a cross-reference search of your files on the following people and organizations to see if they contain additional records related to Mr. Gray:

(1) President George Herbert Walker Bush, to whom the subject served as White House Counsel
(2) Chief Justice Earl Warren, to whom the subject was a law clerk
(3) The Atlantic Counsel, on whose board the subject served
(4) The European Institute, on whose board the subject served
(5) FreedomWorks, on whose board the subject served
(6) The Federalist Society, of which the subject was a member

REQUEST FOR FEE WAIVER

I respectfully request that all fees related to this request be waived.

Public Interest Factors:

1. The subject of the request must concern identifiable operations or activities of the Federal Government. My request satisfies this factor because it seeks records created or maintained by the FBI.

2. The records must be likely to contribute to the understanding of the subject of the request. My request satisfies this factor because Mr. Gray has recently died, so the Bureau may now be able to release records that were not previously available via the FOIA/PA.

3. The disclosure must contribute to the understanding of the public—meaning a reasonably broad audience of persons interested in the subject—as opposed to the individual understanding of the requester. My request satisfies this factor because Mr. Gray was a public figure. He served as White House Counsel to George H. W. Bush and was the U.S. Ambassador to the European Union. News obituaries for Mr. Gray appeared in the New York Times, the Washington Post, and other national media. Thus, a broad audience of persons will likely be interested in the records I seek. I will also make any records available online for free via muckrock.com, a FOIA-and-journalism site that lets people share the results of their FOIA requests and encourages journalism around them.

4. The public's understanding must be enhanced by the disclosure to a significant extent. My request likely satisfies this factor because Mr. Gray has recently died—meaning that the Bureau can now release responsive records that it could not have released until now. Given Mr. Gray's government service as a high-level advisor and employee in the executive and judicial branches, the public's understanding of Mr. Gray, his work, and the work of the government will likely be enhanced significantly.

Commercial Interest Factors

1. The existence and magnitude of a commercial interest: I have no commercial interest whatsoever in these records; I am just an inquisitive citizen. Thus, this factor cuts in favor of a fee waiver.

2. The primary interest in disclosure, i.e., whether disclosure is primarily in the commercial interest of the requester: I have zero commercial interest in disclosure, therefore the public interest outweighs my (nonexistent) private interest.

Conclusion:

On balance, all of the Bureau's regulatory factors tilt decisively in favor of granting me a fee waiver. If you do decide to charge me fees, please notify me in advance if you anticipate that those fees will exceed $25.

Thank you for your timely attention to this request.

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1593177-000
communications.communication:
Dear OIP:

I hearby appeal the Bureau's denial of my request for a fee waiver for my FOIPA Request No. 1593177-000 .

1. The Bureau states that my request failed to meet at least one of the four public interest factors, but it does not say which factor or factors I failed to satisfy or why. This alone is reason enough to reverse the Bureau's decision, because it makes it impossible for the requestor to meaningfully respond to the denial—rendering the denial arbitrary and capricious, an abuse of discretion, and a denial of due process.

2. My request meets the legal standard for a fee waiver. The subject of the request was a public figure, with news obituaries of his death appearing in major newspapers, including the New York Times and the Washington Post. Responsive records will be of great interest to historians, political scientists, scholars, the legal academy, and many others. I am making this request via MuckRock.com, which will automatically make all responsive records available to the general public for free. There is simply no reason to deny this fee waiver.

3. I incorporate by reference the additional arguments I made in my initial request for a fee waiver.

Thank you for your consideration of this appeal.

Most sincerely,

Nicholas Marritz

title: Protection From Abuse (PFA) Orders in Pennsylvania

communications.subject: Pennsylvania Right to Know Act Request: Protection From Abuse (PFA) Orders in Pennsylvania
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Pennsylvania Right to Know Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records containing data on Protection From Abuse (PFA) Orders in Pennsylvania, including the information included below, from January 1, 2019 to December 31, 2023, broken down by year and county, ideally at an individual case level. 

1. The total number of Protection From Abuse (PFA) order petitions filed
2. The total number of PFAs granted, broken down by temporary and final orders
3. The total number of PFAs denied, broken down by temporary and final orders
4. The total number of PFAs that prohibit respondents from possessing firearms, broken down by temporary and final orders
5. The total number of PFAs that require relinquishment of firearms, broken down by temporary and final orders
6. The total number of PFAs where firearms were successfully relinquished to a law enforcement agency
7. The total number of PFAs where firearms were successfully relinquished to a licensed firearm dealer (FFL)
8. The total number of PFAs where firearms were successfully relinquished to a commercial armory
9. The total number of PFAs where firearms were successfully relinquished to an attorney at law who was in an attorney-client relationship with the respondent
10. The total number of PFAs where no firearms were relinquished due to the respondent stating they don’t have any
11. The total number of PFAs where firearms were ordered to be relinquished but were not relinquished 
12. The total number of firearms relinquished to law enforcement
13. The total number of firearms relinquished to FFLs 
14. The total number of firearms relinquished to commercial armories
15. The total number of firearms relinquished to attorneys at law
16. The total number of firearms returned after the expiration of the order
17. The total number of firearms that were not returned after the expiration of the order because the respondent was prohibited from firearm possession

I greatly appreciate any help you can provide. 

At a minimum, I am looking for the number of orders granted and how many required relinquishment of firearms, irrespective of whether you have or are able to share any of the other requested information. 

If there is any information listed above that you do collect and can share, I will take whatever you are able to provide.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Mackey O'Keefe

title: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (Brookfield Police Department)

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (Brookfield Police Department)
communications.communication:
To whoever it may concern: 

This letter constitutes a request pursuant to the Public Records Act, G.L. c.66, §10, for public records in the custody of your school district. Under the Criminal Justice Reform Act,  school districts and law enforcement agencies must “specify the manner and division of responsibility for collecting and reporting the school-based arrests, citations and court referrals of students to the Department of Elementary and Secondary Education” (DESE).   DESE began collecting data on school-related arrests in the 2018-19 school year. In the 2019-20 school year, DESE has expanded that collection to include data on all referrals to law enforcement.  DESE has defined these terms as follows, borrowing the same definitions used by the U.S. Department of Education since its 2009 Civil Rights Data Collection.  

A school-related arrest “[r]efers to an arrest of a student for any activity conducted on school grounds, during off campus school activities (including while taking school transportation), or due to a referral by any school official. All school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”  

A referral to law enforcement “[i]s an action by which a student is reported to any law enforcement agency or official, including a school police unit, for an incident that occurs on school grounds, during school-related events, or while taking school transportation, regardless of whether official action is taken. Citations, tickets, court referrals, and school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”   


I request the following public records, as defined in G. L. c. 4, § 7 (twenty-sixth): 

1.	An extract of your records management system or database that includes each school-related arrest and each referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). Specifically, we request an extract of the database to include the following columns:
a.	Date of arrest or referral to law enforcement
b.	Time of arrest or referral to law enforcement
c.	Charge (or charges)
d.	Whether the individual(s) was arrested or referred to law enforcement
e.	Sex of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
f.	Age of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
g.	Race of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
h.	Ethnicity of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
i.	Disability status of the individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
j.	Whether the individual arrested or referred to law enforcement is a student at the school.
k.	Name of arresting officer, if applicable, and 
l.	Badge number of the arresting officer or the officer that referred the youth to law enforcement, as applicable.

2.	If such an extract of the database in question 1 is not possible, please provide school incident reports on each school-related arrest and referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). 

3.	A copy of any active standard operating procedures developed with the police department and/or other law enforcement agencies regarding police placement or activity in your corresponding school;  and,

4.	Any records instructing or informing police personnel of, or otherwise describing data reporting requirements and procedures for complying with G.L. c. 71 § 37P(b).

5.	The cost to the school district of assigning a school resource officer to each school; and, 

6.	The total number of school resource officers and total number of guidance counselors for each school in your district for school years 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and,

7.	The total number and a brief description of 911 calls from schools in your district to local police departments conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022, and, 

8.	A description of the proposed budget for mental, social, or emotional health support personnel for the school district.

As this request involves a matter of public interest and will not be used for any commercial purpose, we ask that all fees associated with this request be waived pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(k). The purpose of this request is to determine whether your school district and police department are complying with their reporting obligations under the Criminal Justice Reform Act.  “The public has an interest in knowing whether public servants are carrying out their duties in an efficient and law-abiding manner.”    

It would be ill-advised to impose a fee for data that your school district may have failed to report in violation of statutory and regulatory duty.  Moreover, as you know, municipalities with a population of over 20,000 may not assess a fee for the first 2 hours of time spent searching for, compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. Finally, pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(i), a records access officer shall assess no fee greater than the lowest hourly rate of a person capable of compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. In the event that a charge is incurred for this request which you will not waive, please so indicate and include an itemization of estimated good faith costs.
 
Please provide public records to a requestor in an electronic format unless the record is not available in an electronic format. G.L.c. 66, § 6A(d). 

The Public Records Act requires that you comply with this request within ten (10) business days following receipt. If you believe that documents or data responsive to any request herein is not public record and thus not subject to disclosure, please set forth in writing the specific reasons for such assertion, including the specific exemption or exemptions that you believe apply.  To the extent that you determine that records need to be redacted in order to be produced under any law protecting the privacy of named individuals, please do so rather than withholding them in their entirety.

If you have any questions about this request, or need additional time to respond, please contact me by phone at (617)-373-5862 or by email at k.stathulis@northeastern.edu. Thank you in advance for your prompt response to this request.
	
Sincerely, 


Katherine Stathulis, Esq.
Center for Public Interest, Advocacy, and Collaboration
Northeastern University School of Law

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: USMS files re: Frank Cali
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All records concerning FRANK PAUL CALI, a former federal prisoner who is listed by Bureau of Prisons as having had Register Number: 75768-053 and his date of birth listed on Wikipedia is March 26, 1965. Frank Paul Cali was also known as "Francesco Paolo Augusto Calì" and "Franky Boy." He was reported by DOJ as being arrested February 7, 2008. He was tried in United States v. Agate (1:08-cr-00076) District Court, Eastern District of New York.

Cali is widely reported to have died March 13, 2019 in Staten Island, NY (see attached article from the NY Times). Records concerning Cali as a subject should thus be assumed exempt from the FOIA Exemption 6, 7(C) and the Privacy Act.

Please conduct a search of all US Marshals Service systems of records for both main-file records and cross-reference records for all relevant names, agencies and companies. 

US Marshals Service systems of records of interest include (but are not limited to) the Internal Affairs System; U.S. Marshals Service Prisoner Processing and Population Management-Prisoner Tracking System; Warrant Information Network (WIN); Witness Security Files Information System; and Inappropriate Communications-Threat Information System. 

Please also search the DOJ-wide system of records, DOJ-005 Nationwide Joint Automated Booking System (JABS).

If any potentially responsive records have been destroyed and/or transferred to NARA, then I request copies of the destruction or transfer slips as well as any other documentation relating to, mentioning or describing said transfer or destruction, to include but not be limited to confirmation that USMS has no other copies of said records.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

T. McElwee

communications.communication:
I hereby APPEAL the United States Marshals' final determination and production in Freedom of Information Act Request No.2021-USMS-362915 ("All records regarding Frank Paul Cali"), on grounds of an inadequate search and/or production. 

In its final production, the agency provided only a USM-129 about the subject Frank Paul Cali. Upon information and belief, the agency is likely to have further records --for instance, a USM-312 ("Personal History of Defendant") record. As this was not provided, I believe the agency performed a perfunctory and inadequate search of only one class of record, that did not meet the requirement of "a search reasonably calculated to uncover all relevant documents" (see Truitt v. Department of State, 897 F. 2d 540 - Court of Appeals, Dist. of Columbia Circuit 1990). 

My prayer for relief is that the agency remand this case with instructions to broaden its search to all forms and record types that would reasonbly apply to an individual such as Frank Paul Cali, a career criminal and high ranking member of organized crime.

Sincerely,
T. McElwee
